  "summary": "At the Pirate's Flag Hotel, Mrs. Castle expresses concern to Colonel Weston and various inspectors regarding the reputation of her inn following the strangulation of Mrs. Marshall. She explains that the property is isolated by the tide and protected by a gated jetty and impassable rocks, though Detective Inspector Colgate suggests that intruders could potentially land at a cove using small boats. Mrs. Castle identifies her staff, including George, the beach and guest manager, and William, the gardener. She also lists the hotel employees: four maids, a barman named Henry, a cook with two assistants, and a chief waiter named Albert with three assistants.\n\nColonel Weston then interviews Kenneth Marshall, the second husband of the deceased Elena Marshall. Marshall states that he and his wife had been married for four years. He claims that while her beauty and acting career likely attracted envy from other women, he knows of no men who bore her ill will. He mentions that she had met a Mr. Redfern once at a cocktail party but is unsure about other guests. Marshall reports that the last time he saw his wife was around nine o'clock that morning, when she was in her room opening mail consisting of bills. He adds that she typically eats breakfast in bed and usually does not come downstairs until near eleven o'clock. Hercule Poirot observes that if she had appeared at ten o'clock, it would have been unusual.",
